{
  "abstract" : [
    {
      "text" : "Protocol requirements and protocol extension members may be accessed via a conformance constraint on a generic parameter, an opaque result type, or via the protocol type itself:",
      "type" : "text"
    }
  ],
  "hierarchy" : {
    "paths" : [
      [
        "doc:\/\/diagnostics\/documentation\/diagnostics",
        "doc:\/\/diagnostics\/documentation\/diagnostics\/diagnostic-groups"
      ]
    ]
  },
  "identifier" : {
    "interfaceLanguage" : "swift",
    "url" : "doc:\/\/diagnostics\/documentation\/diagnostics\/existential-member-access-limitations"
  },
  "kind" : "article",
  "metadata" : {
    "role" : "article",
    "roleHeading" : "Article",
    "title" : "Using protocol members with references to `Self` or `Self`-rooted associated types (ExistentialMemberAccess)"
  },
  "primaryContentSections" : [
    {
      "content" : [
        {
          "anchor" : "overview",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Overview",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\/\/ An appropriately constrained generic parameter.",
            "func foo<T: CustomStringConvertible>(arg: T) {",
            "  let description: String = arg.description",
            "}",
            "",
            "do {",
            "  \/\/ An appropriately constrained opaque result type.",
            "  func foo() -> some CustomStringConvertible { true }",
            "",
            "  let description: String = foo().description",
            "}",
            "",
            "\/\/ The protocol type.",
            "func foo(arg: CustomStringConvertible) {",
            "  let description: String = arg.description",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "swift",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "While the former two options enable full access to the protocol interface, not all members may be accessible when the protocol is used as a type and not a constraint. Specifically, a protocol member cannot be accessed on a protocol type when its type signature contains a reference to ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " or a ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : "-rooted associated type. Accessing such members on a protocol type is not supported because today the compiler does not have a well-defined meaning and means of representation for  ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " and  ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : "-rooted associated types with respect to a protocol type  ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "P",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ".  As a result, the following code is not allowed:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "protocol Shape {",
            "  func matches(_ other: Self) -> Bool",
            "}",
            "",
            "func foo(_ shape: Shape) {",
            "  \/\/ error: member 'matches' cannot be used on value of protocol type 'Shape'; use a generic constraint instead",
            "  shape.matches(shape)",
            "}",
            "",
            "func foo(_ arg: Identifiable) {",
            "  \/\/ error: member 'id' cannot be used on value of protocol type 'Identifiable'; use a generic constraint instead",
            "  _ = arg.id",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "swift",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "An exception to this limitation are members that contain ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " only in ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Covariance_and_contravariance_(computer_science)",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " position (such as a method result type), where  ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " can be safely substituted with the protocol or protocol composition type used to access the member — a representable supertype. On the other hand, resorting to this ploy in contravariant parameter type position, like allowing one to pass a type-erased value to a method that accepts ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Self",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ", is not type-safe and would expose the opportunity to pass in an argument of non-matching type.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "protocol Shape {",
            "  func duplicate() -> Self",
            "}",
            "",
            "func duplicateShape(_ shape: Shape) -> Shape {",
            "  return shape.duplicate \/\/ OK, produces a value of type 'Shape'",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "swift",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Most use cases involving usage of protocol members that fall under the above restriction can instead be supported by constrained generics, opaque result types, or manual type-erasing wrappers. To learn more, see the sections on ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/docs.swift.org\/swift-book\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language\/protocols",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : ", ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/docs.swift.org\/swift-book\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language\/generics",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : ", and ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/docs.swift.org\/swift-book\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language\/opaquetypes",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " in the Language Guide. For a better understanding of existential types in particular, and an in-depth exploration of the relationships among these built-in abstraction models, we recommend reading ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/forums.swift.org\/t\/improving-the-ui-of-generics\/22814",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : ".",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
  ],
